    detailedAnalysis: "## Introduction\nThe delisting of Japan Airlines from BSE and NSE has sent shockwaves among its shareholders. The airline's stock price has been under pressure due to low trading volumes, and the delisting is expected to further impact its ability to raise capital.\n## Background\nJapan Airlines was listed on the BSE and NSE in 2012, after its initial public offering (IPO). However, the airline's stock price has been volatile, and the trading volumes have been low. The delisting is a result of the airline's failure to meet the minimum trading volume requirements of the exchanges.\n## Impact on Shareholders\nThe delisting will affect the 6 lakh shareholders of Japan Airlines, who will no longer be able to trade their shares on the BSE and NSE. The shareholders are advised to sell their shares before the delisting becomes effective, to avoid any potential losses. According to Rohan Rajiv, an analyst at Kotak Securities, 'The delisting of Japan Airlines is a negative development for the shareholders, and they should consider selling their shares to avoid any further losses.'\n\n---\n\nAuthor: Shiva Sandeep\n\nTelegram: @its_terabyte\n\nWhatsApp:\n\n*Default WhatsApp profile image placeholder*\n\nPublished by PulseTrends\n\n---",
