    opportunities: ["Lower oil prices could reduce inflationary pressures globally, boosting consumer spending and economic growth.", "Sanctions relief could unlock Iran’s $1 trillion economy, creating new trade and investment opportunities.", "Reduced geopolitical risk may encourage capital flows into emerging markets and infrastructure projects."],
    outlook: "## What Happens Next?\nThe road ahead is fraught with challenges. Here’s what to watch in the coming weeks and months:\n\n1. **Congressional Pushback**: US lawmakers have already introduced bills to block the deal, and a Republican-controlled House could complicate implementation. Expect legal battles and potential delays.\n2. **Iran’s Compliance**: Tehran must now prove it can adhere to nuclear restrictions. Any backtracking could trigger snapback sanctions, sending oil prices soaring again.\n3. **Regional Reactions**: Saudi Arabia and Israel, both staunch opponents of the deal, may take steps to counterbalance Iran’s resurgence. Could we see a new arms race in the Middle East?\n4. **Market Adjustments**: Energy traders will be closely monitoring Iran’s oil production. If output ramps up faster than expected, prices could fall further—good news for consumers, bad news for producers.\n5. **Long-Term Trade**: With sanctions easing, companies from Europe to Asia are already eyeing Iran’s vast consumer market. Expect a flurry of deals in sectors like automotive, pharmaceuticals, and telecommunications.\n\nThe next 90 days will be critical. If both sides can navigate the political minefields, this deal could mark the beginning of a new era in Middle East geopolitics. If not, we could be looking at another round of brinkmanship—and market turbulence.",
