    risks: ["Sustaining momentum: The USMNT’s success could be a one-off if the team fails to qualify for future tournaments or underperforms in upcoming competitions.", "Over-commercialization: The influx of advertising and sponsorship dollars could alienate fans if the sport becomes too corporate or loses its grassroots appeal.", "Infrastructure challenges: Youth soccer programs and MLS teams may struggle to keep up with the surge in demand, leading to overcrowding and burnout."],
    opportunities: ["Youth development: The USMNT’s victory could inspire a new generation of players, leading to long-term growth in talent and participation.", "Broadcast innovation: The surge in streaming viewership presents an opportunity for tech companies and broadcasters to pioneer new ways of consuming soccer.", "Global expansion: The U.S. could leverage its newfound soccer prominence to become a hub for international clubs, tournaments, and investment."],
    outlook: "## What Happens Next? The Road Ahead for U.S. Soccer\nThe USMNT’s World Cup victory has set the stage for a transformative period in American soccer, but the real work is just beginning. Here’s what to watch in the coming months and years:\n\n1. **MLS Expansion and Investment:** With interest in soccer at an all-time high, MLS is poised for a new wave of expansion. Cities like San Diego, Las Vegas, and Atlanta have already submitted bids for new franchises, and existing teams are investing heavily in stadium upgrades. Expect to see more European clubs partnering with MLS teams, similar to Manchester City’s affiliation with New York City FC.\n\n2. **Youth Soccer Boom:** The post-1994 World Cup era saw a surge in youth soccer participation, and history could repeat itself. Organizations like U.S. Soccer and the U.S. Youth Soccer Association are already reporting increased inquiries from parents. The challenge will be ensuring that the growth is sustainable and inclusive, rather than just a flash in the pan.\n\n3. **Broadcast Rights Bonanza:** The next round of World Cup broadcast rights negotiations will be fierce. With the 2026 tournament co-hosted by the U.S., Canada, and Mexico, expect bids to shatter previous records. Fox Sports, ESPN, and even tech giants like Amazon and Apple could enter the fray, driving up costs—and expectations.\n\n4. **USWNT’s Turn in the Spotlight:** The U.S. Women’s National Team will have a chance to build on the USMNT’s success when they host the 2027 Women’s World Cup. With the women’s game growing globally, the tournament could be another ratings blockbuster—and a chance to prove that soccer’s popularity in America isn’t a one-off.\n\n5. **The Global Stage:** The USMNT’s victory has elevated the team’s status on the world stage. Expect to see more high-profile friendlies against top-tier opponents, as well as increased scrutiny from FIFA and other governing bodies. The team’s success could also influence the future of the World Cup, with the U.S. pushing for more influence in global soccer politics.\n\nThe USMNT’s World Cup win wasn’t just a triumph—it was a catalyst. The question now is whether the momentum can be sustained, or if this is just the beginning of a much larger story.",
    conclusion: "The USMNT’s World Cup victory has done more than just bring a trophy to American shores—it’s rewritten the rules of engagement for soccer in the U.S. The record ratings, the advertiser frenzy, and the cultural moment have proven that soccer isn’t just a niche sport anymore; it’s a mainstream powerhouse with the potential to rival the NFL and NBA. But with great opportunity comes great responsibility. The challenge now is to build on this momentum, invest in the future, and ensure that the USMNT’s triumph isn’t just a fleeting moment, but the start of a new era. One thing is certain: the world is watching—and for the first time, America is ready to answer.",
