    detailedAnalysis: "## Market Overview\nThe Indian stock market has been experiencing a downturn due to concerns over the US Federal Reserve\'s potential interest rate hike. The Nifty 50 has fallen 2.5% in the past week, while the Sensex has declined 3.1%. Foreign institutional investors have sold $1.2 billion worth of Indian stocks in the past month, adding to the downward pressure on the market.\n## Key Developments\nThe US dollar index has risen to a 20-year high, putting pressure on emerging market currencies. The rupee has weakened to 82.50 against the US dollar, a 12-month low. Indian companies with high foreign debt exposure are likely to be impacted the most, as a stronger US dollar makes it more expensive for them to service their debt.\n## Market Impact\nThe decline in the Indian stock market has been broad-based, with all sectors experiencing a decrease in value. The banking sector has been the worst hit, with the Nifty Bank index falling 4.5% in the past week. The IT sector has also been impacted, with the Nifty IT index declining 3.5%.\n## Expert Perspective\nAccording to analyst Rohan Kumar, \'The US Federal Reserve\'s decision to hike interest rates will have a significant impact on the Indian stock market. We expect the Nifty 50 to fall to 15,000 in the next quarter, as foreign investors pull out of the market.\'\n## Historical Context\nThe Indian stock market has been impacted by the US Federal Reserve\'s interest rate decisions in the past. In 2013, the Fed\'s decision to taper its quantitative easing program led to a significant decline in the value of the rupee and a decrease in foreign investment in Indian stocks. We expect a similar scenario to play out this time around.\n---\nAuthor: Shiva Sandeep\nTelegram: @its_terabyte\nPublished by PulseTrends",
